The Ode is addressed to M. Vipsanius Agrippa, the friend and counsellor of Augustus, and the greatest commender of his reign. He finally defeated Sextus Pompeius at Naulochus in Bc. 56, and commanded at Actium in nc. 51. After the death os Marcellus (and consequently, it would seem, alter the publication of this Ode) he was married by Augustus to his daughter Julia (nc. ar); was asso- ciated with him (ra-c, 18) in the Tribunitian power, and was looked upon as his intended successor. He died four years before Horace, in rac. 12. Horace speaks of his popularityin Sat. 2. 3. 185 ; of his subjugation oi the Cantabri in Epp. 1. 12. 26; ol his engineering exploit of turning the Lucrine lake into a harbour, though without mentioning his name, in A.
